    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory. For each file, compute and return a compact summary (limit lists to top 20 entries):\n1) total number of rows; 2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp); 3) top 20 unique cmdb_id values (alphabetical or by frequency if many); and 4) list of unique KPI/trace/log field names: for metric.csv return the top 50 unique kpi_name values (or all if fewer); for trace.csv return the top 50 unique trace_name values; for log.csv return the top 50 unique log_name values. For error_logs.csv return the top 20 unique message samples (shortened to first 200 characters each). Return the results as a JSON object with keys metric, trace, log, error_logs, each containing the requested summary fields. Keep outputs compact and do not print raw full tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have already loaded all telemetry files. Metric data spans 10:00–11:00 (full pre-incident and incident window) with heavy coverage and many container/node KPIs (node-6 metrics are prominent). Trace and log data are concentrated in the incident window 10:30–10:59/11:00 and show frontend and checkoutservice activity. error_logs.csv is empty. From this, metrics are the best first signal source to narrow suspects (must calculate global thresholds using full metric series, then inspect the 10:30–11:00 window).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) aggregate the FULL available series and compute two global thresholds: P95 and P5 (use all rows for that component-KPI in metric.csv). 2) Then filter metric.csv to the incident window inclusive: timestamps between 1647829800 and 1647831600 (these correspond to 2022-03-21 10:30 → 11:00 UTC+8). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the incident window, detect anomalies where value >= P95 OR value <= P5 (use the P95/P5 computed from the full series). 4) Produce two compact outputs (store intermediate tables in kernel variables but only return summaries):\n   A) Top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) rows ranked by anomaly count in the incident window. For each row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Limit to top 20.\n   B) Top 20 cmdb_id aggregated by total anomaly_count across all KPIs (columns: cmdb_id, total_anomaly_count, number_of_KPIs_with_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_for_component). Limit to top 20.\nReturn the results as JSON with two keys: per_kpi_anomalies and per_component_anomalies. Keep outputs compact and do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step completed metric-level anomaly detection. Key findings: adservice and adservice2 show the largest and broadest metric anomalies (many KPIs anomalous for the entire 31-minute window starting at 2022-03-21T10:30:00+08:00). Frontend pods and many downstream services also show widespread anomalies, but metrics alone cannot determine which faulty component is the root cause for each of the two failures. Next we must use traces to disambiguate which service/pod is the downstream faulty component in request call chains and to identify timestamps where request errors or latency spikes began. Trace analysis should compute global thresholds per (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full trace.csv, then detect anomalies in the 10:30–11:00 window (1647829800–1647831600). Focus on trace fields that indicate failures/latency/traffic changes (trace.*.error_rate, trace.*.duration_*, trace.*.row_count) to localize potential root cause components and their first anomaly timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv only: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the full available time series in trace.csv. 2) Filter trace.csv to timestamps between 1647829800 and 1647831600 inclusive (2022-03-21 10:30 → 11:00 UTC+8). 3) Restrict analysis to trace_name values that contain any of the substrings: 'error_rate', 'duration', or 'row_count' (these indicate failures, latency, or traffic drops). 4) Within the filtered window, flag anomalies where value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5 (use the P95/P5 computed from the full series per (cmdb_id,trace_name)). 5) Return two compact JSON aggregates (store intermediate data in kernel variables but only return summaries):\n   A) Top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) by anomaly_count_in_window. For each row return: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, global_p5, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (epoch and local), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Limit rows to top 20.\n   B) Top 20 cmdb_id aggregated by total trace anomaly_count across trace_names. For each return: cmdb_id, total_trace_anomaly_count, number_of_trace_names_with_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_for_component (epoch and local). Limit rows to top 20.\nKeep outputs compact; do not return raw time series or full tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows many trace error_rate/duration/row_count metrics pinned at 0.0 starting at 2022-03-21T10:30:00+08:00. Metric analysis shows broad anomalies (adservice/adservice2 and many frontend/checkout pods) also starting at the window start. This pattern suggests a systemic traffic drop or telemetry collection interruption at 10:30. To determine whether there are one or two distinct failures within 10:30–11:00 and to localize the root cause components and exact occurrence times, we must inspect trace row_count time series for request traffic drops (zero/near-zero) and identify contiguous zero/low-traffic intervals per component. If we find two separate zero/low-traffic incidents with different start times, those will correspond to the two failures; if only a single continuous outage exists, we must use logs to differentiate two failure events within it. error_logs.csv is empty, so rely on trace row_count and log.csv next.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv only: 1) From the full trace.csv (do NOT filter before computing thresholds), identify all trace_name values that contain 'row_count'. 2) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P5 (using all available rows for that pair). 3) Filter trace.csv to the incident window timestamps between 1647829800 and 1647831600 inclusive. 4) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in the window, mark points where value <= global_P5 OR value == 0.0. 5) Compress consecutive marked points into contiguous intervals (faults). For each interval produce: cmdb_id, trace_name, interval_start_epoch, interval_end_epoch, duration_minutes (count of timestamps), min_value_in_interval, max_value_in_interval. 6) Return two compact summaries (store intermediate tables in kernel variables but only return these summaries):\n   A) Top 50 intervals sorted by interval_start_epoch (earliest first). Limit fields to those above.\n   B) For each cmdb_id that has at least one interval, return cmdb_id, number_of_intervals, earliest_interval_start_epoch, total_minutes_in_intervals. Limit to top 20 cmdb_ids by total_minutes_in_intervals.\nKeep outputs compact and do not return raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "You compressed row_count trace anomalies into contiguous low/zero-traffic intervals and found many short, concurrent intervals that mostly start at the window start (2022-03-21T10:30:00+08:00). Checkoutservice and frontend pods show the largest aggregate impact. This suggests a system-wide traffic/telemetry disruption beginning at 10:30; however the task states there were two failures in 10:30–11:00, so we must locate distinct failure occurrence times inside the window. To do that we should examine high-level ingress/ frontend row_count signals (trace.from_root.row_count and trace.from_frontend-*.row_count / frontend.trace.self.row_count) aggregated by minute across the system to find when request traffic dropped or changed sharply (this will reveal one or more failure start times). After we identify candidate failure start times, we will examine logs and relevant metrics around those exact minutes to localize the root-cause component and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv: 1) Filter rows to timestamps between 1647829800 and 1647831600 inclusive. 2) From those rows select only trace records whose trace_name contains 'row_count' AND (trace_name contains 'from_root' OR trace_name contains 'from_frontend' OR trace_name contains 'from_frontend2' OR (cmdb_id startswith 'frontend' AND trace_name == 'trace.self.row_count')). 3) Aggregate by timestamp (sum the value) to compute total_ingress_row_count_per_minute. 4) Return a compact result with: for each timestamp in the window (sorted ascending) return epoch timestamp, local time, total_ingress_row_count. Also return a separate small summary: the 5 minutes with the lowest total_ingress_row_count (each with epoch, local time, and total). Limit outputs to the per-minute series (up to 31 rows) and the 5-row min-summary. Keep intermediate tables in kernel variables but only return the requested compact output." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level anomaly scan, trace analysis (including row_count interval compression and ingress aggregation), and log aggregations. Findings so far: (A) a broad set of metric anomalies and many trace fields pinned/low starting at 2022-03-21T10:30:00+08:00—checkout and frontend paths show many short low/zero row_count intervals starting at 10:30, while many metrics (notably adservice/adservice2 and frontend pods) were flagged anomalous across the whole window; (B) ingress row_count aggregated per minute is steady (~6.6k–8.0k) for most of the window but drops abruptly to 0.0 at 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00. Logs show no error_count spikes and row_count in logs remains >0 throughout the window, so application-level logs do not show errors. Interpretation: there are two distinct notable events inside the 10:30–11:00 window: (1) a systemic anomaly beginning at 10:30 affecting many traces/metrics (likely either a widespread telemetry/tracing collection issue or a partial traffic interruption affecting many call paths), and (2) a hard ingress drop to zero at 11:00 (an abrupt event that likely corresponds to either traffic shutdown or telemetry/collector outage at that minute). To confirm the exact root-cause components and reasons we need to check metric-level deltas at the 11:00 abrupt drop to identify which components/resources changed right at 11:00 (this will help determine whether the 11:00 event was caused by node/network/agent problems). For the 10:30 systemic anomaly we will next inspect resource KPIs (CPU/memory/network/disk) for top candidate components (adservice/adservice2, frontend pods, and node-6) to see which resource shows the most significant sustained deviation starting at 10:30.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only: 1) Extract rows for timestamps 1647831540 (2022-03-21T10:59:00+08:00) and 1647831600 (2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00). 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present at both timestamps, compute value_1059, value_1100, and delta = value_1100 - value_1059. Also compute percent_change = (delta / value_1059 * 100) where value_1059 != 0 (if value_1059 == 0 set percent_change to null). 3) Return the top 20 rows sorted by absolute delta (largest magnitude changes). For each row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, value_1059, value_1100, delta, percent_change, earliest_ts_local (for 1647831540) and latest_ts_local (for 1647831600). 4) Also return a short summary listing how many distinct cmdb_id had any metric changes at these two timestamps and the top 5 cmdb_id by number of changed KPIs. Keep outputs compact and do not return raw full series." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds, detected anomalies in metrics and traces, compressed trace row_count faults, aggregated ingress row_count per minute, summarized logs, and compared metrics at 10:59 vs 11:00. Findings so far: (1) a widespread set of anomalies and many low/zero trace row_count intervals beginning at 2022-03-21T10:30:00+08:00 affecting checkout/frontend paths and many services — likely a systemic traffic perturbation or telemetry sampling change starting at 10:30; (2) an abrupt drop of aggregated ingress row_count to 0.0 at 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00, coincident with very large jumps in node-6 disk/inode metrics and broad KPI changes across many frontends at 11:00. These suggest two distinct events: the 10:30 systemic anomaly (partial/trace-related disruption) and the 11:00 abrupt event (possible node/collector/storage or telemetry agent disruption or real traffic shutdown). To distinguish whether 11:00's zero ingress is due to traffic stopping or telemetry/tracing/agent/collector outage, we must check presence of trace, metric, and log rows specifically at timestamp 1647831600 (2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00). If logs remain present (application-level) but traces/metrics are absent or show exporter resets on node-6, that points to telemetry agent/collector or node-level issue rather than traffic shutdown. Conversely, if all telemetry and logs show zero rows at 11:00, that indicates a real traffic outage or upstream shutdown. This is not yet conclusive; I will request a compact presence/count check for that exact minute.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For timestamp 1647831600 (2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00) only, inspect metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv. For each file return a compact JSON summary with these fields: 1) total_rows_at_timestamp (integer); 2) top_20_cmdb_id_with_counts (list of up to 20 {cmdb_id, count}); 3) top_20_name_with_counts where 'name' is kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, and log_name for log.csv (list of up to 20 {name, count}). Additionally, for trace.csv explicitly report the count of rows whose trace_name contains 'row_count' and the count of rows whose trace_name contains 'from_root'. Keep outputs compact; do not return full raw rows—only the aggregates above." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the workflow and gathered strong evidence for two distinct events in the 2022-03-21 10:30–11:00 window: (A) a systemic anomaly beginning at 2022-03-21T10:30:00+08:00 that produced many trace metrics pinned at zero or low row_count intervals across frontend→checkout→downstream call paths while application logs show ongoing traffic (log.row_count nonzero and ingress totals remain thousands/minute). This pattern points to a telemetry/tracing collection or sampling disruption (or a partial traffic perturbation affecting traces) starting at 10:30 rather than an application crash—the symptoms are widespread and not accompanied by error_count spikes in logs. (B) an abrupt event at 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00: aggregated ingress row_count dropped to 0.0 at that minute, trace rows are completely missing at 11:00, and metric deltas show very large jumps in node-6 disk and inode metrics at 11:00 plus numerous KPI changes across frontends. Metric rows still exist at 11:00 while trace rows are absent and logs are sparse. This suggests a node-level or telemetry-collector/agent problem occurring at 11:00 (node-6 is a prominent hotspot). We are not yet fully certain whether the 11:00 event was a real traffic shutdown or a telemetry/collector failure; to decide, we need targeted confirmation of node-6 and container start-time / exporter restart signals and more precise evidence of metric-exporter or filesystem/agent restarts at 11:00. Therefore we should inspect container start-time and node disk/inode KPIs across 10:59→11:00 to find restarts or reporting resets that would explain the trace outage at 11:00.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv only, extract rows for timestamps 1647831540 and 1647831600 (10:59 and 11:00). Restrict to rows whose kpi_name contains any of these substrings: 'container_start_time', 'container.start_time', 'system.disk', 'system.fs.inodes', 'container_fs_usage', 'container_fs_reads', 'container_fs_writes', 'container_memory_usage_MB'. For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present at either timestamp, compute value_1059 (value at 1647831540 if present), value_1100 (value at 1647831600 if present), delta = value_1100 - value_1059 (use null if one side missing), and percent_change where applicable (null if division by zero). Return a compact table limited to the top 50 rows sorted by absolute delta (largest first) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, value_1059, value_1100, delta, percent_change. Also return a short aggregate: count of distinct cmdb_id that show any change in a 'container_start_time' kpi between the two timestamps and list those cmdb_id (limit to top 20). Keep outputs compact; do not return raw full time series." }

